cell("markdown","# Algorithms 37-39: Minimax & Game Trees\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Formulate 2-player zero-sum games as a state-space Tree\n2. Implement the Minimax Algorithm to guarantee optimal play\n3. Integrate Minimax into your Tic-Tac-Toe architecture from Batch 3\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 17, Algorithms 31\n**Estimated time:** 90 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapters 37-39"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### Game Trees\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 37:* A game tree represents all possible moves in a game. The current board is the \"root\". Each possible legal move creates a \"child\" branch, leading to a new board state. We can explore the tree to find winning paths.\n\n### The Minimax Algorithm\nIf we explore the tree all the way down to a Win (+1), Loss (-1), or Tie (0), we can work backwards to figure out the best move right now. \n- When it is **Our Turn**, we want to maximize our score. We will choose the child branch with the MAXIMUM score.\n- When it is the **Opponent's Turn**, we must assume they play perfectly. They want to minimize our score. They will choose the child branch with the MINIMUM score.\n\nBy recursively calling Minimax down the tree, we alternatingly take the Max and Min of the children to find the true, guaranteed value of any game state!"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\nIf a board state has 3 possible moves that lead to scores of `[1, 0, -1]`:\nWhat is the Minimax value of this state if it's Our turn? \nWhat is the Minimax value if it's the Opponent's turn?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answer</summary>\nIf it's Our turn, we pick the maximum: `1` (We force a win!).\nIf it's Their turn, they pick the minimum: `-1` (They force us to lose!).\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Minimax Pseudocode\nReview the core Minimax pseudocode:\n```python\ndef minimax(state, is_maximizing):\n    if state.is_terminal(): return state.score()\n    \n    if is_maximizing:\n        best = -infinity\n        for child in state.get_children():\n            best = max(best, minimax(child, False))\n        return best\n    else:\n        best = infinity\n        for child in state.get_children():\n            best = min(best, minimax(child, True))\n        return best\n```\nWhat is the maximum depth this recursion will reach in a standard game of Tic-Tac-Toe?"),
cell("code","# Answer here as a comment!"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 1 — Algorithm Construction\n\n### Step 1: The Tic-Tac-Toe Board State\nBring back your Tic-Tac-Toe Board representation from Algorithms 17. We need to add `get_legal_moves()`, `make_move(move, player)`, and `check_winner()`."),
cell("code","class Board:\n    def __init__(self, state=None):\n        self.state = state if state else [0]*9\n        \n    def get_legal_moves(self):\n        return [i for i, val in enumerate(self.state) if val == 0]\n        \n    def make_move(self, index, player):\n        # Return a NEW Board instance so we don't mutate the current one during tree search!\n        new_state = self.state.copy()\n        new_state[index] = player\n        return Board(new_state)\n        \n    def check_winner(self):\n        # Check rows, cols, diags for 1 (X) or -1 (O)\n        # Return 1 if X wins, -1 if O wins, 0 if tie, None if incomplete\n        # YOUR CODE HERE\n        pass"),
cell("markdown","### Step 2: Implementing Minimax\nWrite `minimax(board, is_maximizing_player)`. Assume X is maximizing (+1) and O is minimizing (-1)."),
cell("code","def minimax(board, is_maximizing):\n    winner = board.check_winner()\n    if winner is not None:\n        return winner # Base case: terminal state\n        \n    if is_maximizing:\n        best_score = -math.inf\n        for move in board.get_legal_moves():\n            # 1. Create child board by making move for X (1)\n            # 2. Call minimax(child, False)\n            # 3. best_score = max(best_score, result)\n            pass\n        return best_score\n    else:\n        best_score = math.inf\n        for move in board.get_legal_moves():\n            # 1. Create child board by making move for O (-1)\n            # 2. Call minimax(child, True)\n            # 3. best_score = min(best_score, result)\n            pass\n        return best_score"),
cell("markdown","### Step 3: Extracting the Best Move\nMinimax returns the *score* of the board, not the move. Write `get_best_move(board, player)` which loops through legal moves, calls Minimax on each, and returns the move with the best score!"),
cell("code","def get_best_move(board, player):\n    best_move = None\n    # if player == 1 (Maximizing):\n    #   best_score = -inf\n    #   loop moves, child = make_move, score = minimax(child, False)\n    #   if score > best_score, update best_move\n    \n    # if player == -1 (Minimizing):\n    #   best_score = inf\n    #   loop moves, child = make_move, score = minimax(child, True)\n    #   if score < best_score, update best_move\n    \n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    pass"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 2 — Experimental Verification\n\n### The Unbeatable AI\nPlay a game against your Minimax AI. Try to beat it! (Spoiler: You can't. The best you can do is tie!)"),
