cell("markdown","# Algorithms 40-42: Neuroevolution & Blondie24\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Combine Neural Networks and Evolutionary Algorithms\n2. Replicate Fogel & Chellapilla's *Blondie24* checkers player\n3. Train networks through pure self-play tournaments without datasets or backpropagation\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 35-36\n**Estimated time:** 180 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapters 40-42"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The Problem with Gradient Descent in Games\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 42:* When training an AI to play Checkers, we don't have a dataset of \"perfect moves\". And we can't easily backpropagate through thousands of discrete game tree decisions.\n\n### Neuroevolution\nInstead of calculating gradients mathematically, we use **Darwinian Evolution**!\n1. **Initialize** 15 random Neural Networks.\n2. **Mutate**: Each network generates a \"child\" with slightly randomized weights.\n3. **Evaluate**: We now have 30 networks. We make them play Checkers against each other in a massive tournament! We track how many games each network wins.\n4. **Select**: We kill the 15 lowest-scoring networks. The 15 best networks survive.\n5. Go back to step 2 and repeat for 800 generations!\n\nThis exact technique was used by Fogel & Chellapilla in 1999 to create *Blondie24*, a Checkers AI that taught itself to achieve an expert rating on an online gaming site, entirely through self-play!"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\nWhy do we mutate the weights randomly instead of trying to calculate which direction is best?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answer</summary>\nBecause the \"fitness landscape\" of a complex game is highly jagged, and we have no mathematical formula to compute the gradient of \"winning a game of checkers\". Random mutation, combined with strict selection, effectively acts as a \"stochastic gradient descent\" that explores the landscape blindly but relentlessly moves uphill toward mastery.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Gaussian Mutation\nWrite a function `mutate(network, mutation_rate=0.05)` that loops through all the weights and biases of a Neural Network and adds random Gaussian noise. `weight += random.gauss(0, mutation_rate)`."),
