cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The Spatial Problem\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 43:* In 2001, Fogel & Chellapilla improved Blondie24 by adding a **Convolutional Layer**. This acts as a spatial preprocessing layer, allowing the network to perceive spatial characteristics of the board at different levels of zoom.\n\nIn a standard MLP, the $8 \\times 8$ checkers board is flattened into a 64-element 1D list. The network completely loses the 2D geometric structure! It doesn't know that square 1 is \"above\" square 9.\n\n### The Convolutional Concept\nA convolutional layer fixes this by processing 2D patches of the board.\nBlondie24 defined subnetworks that look at every possible $3 \\times 3$, $4 \\times 4$, $5 \\times 5$, $6 \\times 6$, $7 \\times 7$, and $8 \\times 8$ subsquare of the board!\n- For an $8 \\times 8$ board, there are 36 possible $3 \\times 3$ subsquares.\n- Each of these 36 patches has its own node in the Convolutional Layer.\n\nThis structure mathematically forces the neural network to \"see\" localized 2D patterns (like an opponent setting up a jump) before making decisions!"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\nWhy did the addition of the convolutional layer increase the number of weights in Blondie24 from 1,742 to 5,047?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answer</summary>\nBecause the input layer now connects to 92 different convolutional nodes ($1 + 4 + 9 + 16 + 25 + 36 + 1$), and each connection processes a 2D patch of inputs, requiring vastly more weight matrices to filter the visual information.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Calculating Subsquares\nIf you have an $N \\times N$ board, how many $K \\times K$ subsquares can fit inside it? \nWrite a function to return the count."),
